T1  - Economic incentives in OPEC oil pricing policy
AU  - Kalymon, Basil A.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 2
IS  - 4
SP  - 337
EP  - 362
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/12/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(76)90007-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387876900079
AB  - This paper deals with the construction and evaluation of economic models of price setting in the world oil market. The possible coalition structures within OPEC are evaluated on the basis of both a long-term optimization model of oil resource utilization and within a simulation model of market sharing. The first model provides insight into the sensitivity of equilibrium prices to size of reserves, demand elasticity and time preferences. The second model is used to evaluate the implications for individual coalition members of alternative pricing policies in conjunction with specific market-sharing agreements. A general assessment of the implications of these economic pressures on oil pricing is provided.
